<mediaPoint id="fig01_14" type="IMG" mediaType="TID1" mediaSize="3" order="17" href="chap01.html#fig01_14"><desc><![CDATA[<b>Figure 1-14</b> Coronal section through the central orbit just posterior to the globe. <span style="font-size:0.8em"><i>(Reproduced with permission from Dutton JJ.</i> Atlas of Clinical and Surgical Orbital Anatomy. <i>Philadelphia: Saunders; 1994.)</i></span>]]></desc><mediaPath src="images/img_p16-2.jpg" thumbSrc="images/img_p16-2.jpg"/></mediaPoint>
<mediaPoint id="fig01_15" type="IMG" mediaType="TID1" mediaSize="3" order="18" href="chap01.html#fig01_15"><desc><![CDATA[<b>Figure 1-15</b> Location of the plane of the section shown in Figure 1-16. <span style="font-size:0.8em"><i>(Reproduced with permission from Dutton JJ.</i> Atlas of Clinical and Surgical Orbital Anatomy. <i>Philadelphia: Saunders; 1994.)</i></span>]]></desc><mediaPath src="images/img_p16-3.jpg" thumbSrc="images/img_p16-3.jpg"/></mediaPoint>
<mediaPoint id="fig01_16" type="IMG" mediaType="TID1" mediaSize="3" order="19" href="chap01.html#fig01_16"><desc><![CDATA[<b>Figure 1-16</b> Axial section through the midorbit at the level of the optic nerve. The third portion of the ophthalmic artery crosses the nerve in the posterior orbit. <span style="font-size:0.8em"><i>(Reproduced with permission from Dutton JJ.</i> Atlas of Clinical and Surgical Orbital Anatomy. <i>Philadelphia: Saunders; 1994.)</i></span>]]></desc><mediaPath src="images/img_p17.jpg" thumbSrc="images/img_p17.jpg"/></mediaPoint>
</mediaMap>
</navPoint>
