<mediaMap>
<mediaPoint id="fig02_19" type="IMG" mediaType="TID1" mediaSize="3" order="61" href="chap02.html#fig02_19"><desc><![CDATA[<b>Figure 2-19</b> Schematic representation of the arrangement of the smooth muscle fibers in the ciliary body. Note the relationship of the ciliary body to the iris, the anterior chamber, the Schlemm canal, and the corneoscleral limbus. <span style="font-size:0.8em"><i>(Reproduced with permission from Snell RS, Lemp MA.</i> Clinical Anatomy of the Eye. <i>Cambridge, MA: Blackwell Scientific Publications; 1989.)</i></span>]]></desc><mediaPath src="images/img_p59.jpg" thumbSrc="images/img_p59.jpg"/></mediaPoint>
</mediaMap>
</navPoint></navPoint>
<navPoint id="navPoint-69" playOrder="78"><navLabel><text>Choroid</text></navLabel><content src="chap02.html#s30"/>
<mediaMap>
<mediaPoint id="fig02_20" type="IMG" mediaType="TID1" mediaSize="3" order="62" href="chap02.html#fig02_20"><desc><![CDATA[<b>Figure 2-20</b> Choroid. The choriocapillaris lies just below the retinal pigment epithelium. Beneath are middle and outer vascular layers and multiple dendritic melanocytes (H&#x0026;E <span style="font-size:130%;vertical-align:middle;">&#215;</span>32). <span style="font-size:0.8em"><i>(Courtesy of Thomas A. Weingeist, PhD, MD.)</i></span>]]></desc><mediaPath src="images/img_p60.jpg" thumbSrc="images/img_p60.jpg"/></mediaPoint>
