<mediaMap>
<mediaPoint id="fig03_11" type="IMG" mediaType="TID1" mediaSize="3" order="95" href="chap03.html#fig03_11"><desc><![CDATA[<b>Figure 3-11</b> Cranial nerve V (trigeminal nerve): pattern of facial sensation. Lesions of the trigeminal sensory nucleus in the brainstem result in an &#x201C;onionskin&#x201D; distribution of altered sensation (regions A, B, and C) delineated by the <i>dashed lines;</i> lesions of the ophthalmic (V<sub>1</sub>), maxillary (V<sub>2</sub>), and mandibular (V<sub>3</sub>) nerves result in the pattern of sensory loss delineated by the <i>solid lines.</i>
	<small><i>(Illustration by Thomas A. Weingeist, PhD, MD.)</i></small>]]></desc><mediaPath src="images/img_p99.jpg" thumbSrc="images/img_p99.jpg"/></mediaPoint>
</mediaMap>
</navPoint>
